<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h2>Tutorial 6. Joining the Hard Mesh with the Chiffon Lining.</h2>
<p></p>
<p><strong>Now is the time to start sewing the body of the corset. </strong>Right now we’re using double-faced fabrics that look the same from both sides. I am talking about the hard mesh and the chiffon. When you work on a see-through corset, it is particularly important to avoid confusion between left and right pattern pieces because the face and the lining look the same. As we were cutting out patterns, we numbered them for easy matching. I had turned the pieces upside down and numbered them from the other side as well. This helps you know which side is a conventional face side (in other words which side should face up). This will prevent us from joining a pair of identical back pieces for example. We are about to join the mesh and the chiffon: all patterns should be carefully arranged so that we can tell the left side from the right one. </p>
<p><strong>Let’s start from the central front piece. </strong>I unpin it and spread it. I’m going to join the chiffon and the mesh fabric now. You should by no means join them all around the perimeter but <strong>only along their vertical edges</strong> or else you’ll end up with a bubble distorting the corset. <strong>You should look to the mesh fabric as a reference since the chiffon is only a covering fabric. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I start joining them.</strong> </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image002.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>Whenever you start performing this operation, it is hard to tell whether you should place drapery fabric over mesh fabric or underneath it. I work with the first piece to test the process. This time after making the first seam I could tell that sewing is uncomfortable with the chiffon on top. </p>
<p><strong>I turn the piece upside down and stitch along the other vertical edge. </strong>Transparent mesh fabric allows me to see the way the chiffon lies and I can spread it, pull it and even it out to match the edges well. </p>
<p><strong>The stitch is made at a presser foot distance. </strong>Don’t worry about the chiffon going beyond the edges of the mesh fabric at the top or down the bottom – this is not relevant at the moment. <strong>The main task is to join the vertical edges of the parts as neatly as possible.</strong> </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image004.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Next I take an intermediate front piece (piece 2). </strong>I unpin it and prepare it for sewing. I recommend unpinning the pieces one by one as the process advances instead of unpinning them all in one go. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image006.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>What I do now might be the most toilsome work in the whole process of making a corset with a plastic mesh base. I keep arranging the chiffon with my finger because there is bias grain along nearly all edges of all narrow pieces. </p>
<p><strong>I take the second intermediate front piece. </strong>I will arrange the pieces in a vertically mirrored fashion and sew them the same way. I look to the pen-written marks not to misrecognize the sides and to make sure the pieces mirror each other. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image008.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I make a vertical stitch along the other side of the pieces.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image010.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p>Don’t be disturbed by minor mismatches of pieces but do try to arrange the chiffon evenly underneath the mesh fabric. Use your finger to spread it when needed. And remember to make sure there are no folds or tucks and <strong>the mesh fabric is covered with the chiffon perfectly evenly.</strong> Horizontal edges should be left as is for now, don’t stitch them up.</p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image012.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I continue sewing the pieces in the same manner one by one. </strong>I highly recommend sewing them in pairs and leaving them on the same thread in a mirrored fashion. This will come in handy later as we start joining the pieces. We will take a pair of pieces at a time and sew their corresponding curved seams.&nbsp; </p>
<p><strong>Now I move on to the side pieces of the front.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image014.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>The central pieces of the back:</strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image016.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>The intermediate pieces of the back:</strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image018.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image020.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>The side pieces of the back:</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_1/transcripts/Tutorial%206_files/image022.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
